{
  format: 1
  name: future-filtered-row-selected-at-its-active-instant
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["#views", "§7.1", "#buckets", "§14.1", "§14.2"]
  tags: ["temporal", "authz", "boundary", "regression"]
  note: '''A filtered temporal read must apply its predicate to the collection`s
    EXTANT (§14.2), not merely to the rows active at the clock — so a row that is
    DORMANT at the clock but active at the queried instant t and that satisfies the
    predicate MUST appear in `.coll[pred].$at(t)`, while a dormant row the predicate
    excludes must NOT. This pins the over-narrowing dual of the filter-bypass fix:
    re-applying the base`s predicate must range over the recovered extant (which
    includes inactive/future rows), never only the empty current-active set.

    §7.1: `.sessions[:s | s.label == "keep"]` ranges over sessions and keeps the
    rows satisfying the predicate. §14.1: `.$at(t)` selects the rows active at t —
    including rows active only in the FUTURE relative to the clock. The composition
    is the sessions rows that satisfy the predicate AND are active at t; a
    future-active `keep` row is one of them.

    Setup: one lifecycle bucket `sessions` with two rows, both on the FUTURE interval
    [2026-06-01, 2026-09-01). At the 2026-01-01 clock both are DORMANT (no session is
    active at the clock, so the materialized current set is empty). The read instant
    2026-07-01 lies inside both intervals. Row `sk` has label "keep"; row `sx` has
    label "leak".

    Step 1 (control, bare temporal at the future instant): `.sessions.$at(t){ label }`
    returns BOTH rows, proving both are extant and active at t even though dormant at
    the clock (so a `keep` row appearing in step 2 is genuine temporal activity, not
    a clock-time artifact).

    Step 2 (target, filtered temporal at the future instant): `.sessions[:s | s.label
    == "keep"].$at(t){ label }` MUST return exactly [{label: "keep"}] — the dormant
    future row that satisfies the predicate and is active at t. A fix that applied the
    predicate only to the clock-active set would return [] (the current set is empty);
    a fix that dropped the predicate would return both rows. Only re-applying the
    predicate to the extant active at t yields the single correct row.'''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.b14.futurefilt@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      // A single lifecycle bucket, dormant at the clock (its rows start in the
      // future), read at an instant inside its future active interval.
      sessions: {
        $key: "id"
        $bucket: { $from: ".starts", $until: ".ends" }
        id: "text"
        label: "text"
        starts: "timestamp"
        ends: "timestamp"
      }
      $public: {
        // Control: a bare temporal read at the future instant returns every row
        // active then, proving both rows are extant and active despite dormancy.
        read_bare: {
          $params: { t: "timestamp" }
          $view: ".sessions.$at(@t) { label }"
        }
        // Target: the filtered temporal read must apply the predicate to the extant
        // active at t, keeping the future `keep` row and excluding `leak`.
        read_filtered: {
          $params: { t: "timestamp" }
          $view: '''.sessions[:s | s.label == "keep"].$at(@t) { label }'''
        }
      }
    }
    $data: {
      // Both rows: interval [2026-06-01T00:00:00Z, 2026-09-01T00:00:00Z), entirely in
      // the future relative to the 2026-01-01 clock, so the bucket is dormant then.
      sessions: {
        sk: { label: "keep", starts: "1780272000000000", ends: "1788220800000000" }
        sx: { label: "leak", starts: "1780272000000000", ends: "1788220800000000" }
      }
    }
  }

  steps: [
    // Control: bare temporal at 2026-07-01T00:00:00Z sees both future-active rows.
    { watch: "public.read_bare", args: { t: "1782864000000000" }, id: "w1"
      expect_init: {
        value: { $unordered: [
          { label: "keep" }
          { label: "leak" }
        ] }
      } }

    // Target: the filtered temporal read keeps only the predicate-selected row that
    // is active at t, proving the predicate is applied to the extant (§14.2) and a
    // future-active matching row is eligible (§14.1) — never [] and never both rows.
    { watch: "public.read_filtered", args: { t: "1782864000000000" }, id: "w2"
      expect_init: {
        value: [
          { label: "keep" }
        ]
      } }
  ]
}
